(195, 'Facebook Wants Great Power&#44; But What About Responsibility?', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:01:49', 'no', 'no', 0),
(196, 'This week the chief of Facebook made an ambitious announcement&#44; though it would have been easy to miss.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:02:58', 'no', 'no', 0),
(197, 'It came Thursday afternoon – around the same time that President Donald Trump held his press conference. While the reality&#45;TV icon is a genius at capturing our attention&#44; the technology leader&#39;s words may prove to be more relevant to our lives&#44; and more radical.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:03:29', 'no', 'no', 0),
(198, 'Mark Zuckerberg posted a nearly 6000&#45;word essay to his page&#44; entitled &#34;Building Global Community.&#34;', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:06:20', 'no', 'no', 0),
(199, 'Many are calling it a &#34;manifesto.&#34; His ambitions are global and his tone&#44; altruistic. Zuckerberg writes: &#34;Our greatest opportunities are now global — like spreading prosperity and freedom&#44; promoting peace and understanding&#44; lifting people out of poverty&#44; and accelerating science.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:08:08', 'no', 'no', 0),
(200, 'Our greatest challenges also need global responses — like ending terrorism&#44; fighting climate change&#44; and preventing pandemics.&#34;', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:09:17', 'no', 'no', 0),
(201, 'Zuckerberg speaks to people who dream of global citizenship&#44; a borderless utopia that many political leaders around the world don&#39;t seem to be offering.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:09:48', 'no', 'no', 0),
(202, '&#34;In times like these&#44; the most important thing we at Facebook can do is develop the social infrastructure to give people the power to build a global community that works for all of us.&#34;', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:12:39', 'no', 'no', 0),
(203, 'And to build this global community&#44; he encourages us to shift how we think about Facebook: stop looking at the app as a means of recreation.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:14:27', 'no', 'no', 0),
(204, 'Instead&#44; think of it as the way you connect to others – for work or for play.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:15:36', 'no', 'no', 0),
(205, 'You can use it as a medium to let the world know about your startup or to recruit parishioners to your church or to announce your presidential campaign or to manage a multinational disaster relief effort.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:16:07', 'no', 'no', 0),
(206, '&#34;Going forward&#44; we will measure Facebook&#39;s progress with groups based on meaningful groups&#44; not groups overall&#44;&#34; he writes.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:18:58', 'no', 'no', 0),
(207, 'He adds that the strengthening of &#34;meaningful online communities&#34; will &#34;strengthen our social fabric.&#34;', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:20:46', 'no', 'no', 0),
(208, 'It sounds noble&#44; but behind that alluring vision is a profound power grab delivered by a savvy politician&#44; say critics.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:21:55', 'no', 'no', 0),
(209, 'At its core&#44; Zuckerberg&#39;s essay reads like a call to give up our open access to the Internet and the freedom that exists in a marketplace with real competition. Rather&#44; Facebook wants us to step into its walled garden – where a handful of company chieftains set the rules – and live our social&#44; economic&#44; and religious lives inside it.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:22:26', 'no', 'no', 0),
(210, 'What he doesn&#39;t address in his essay&#44; however&#44; are the responsibilities that come with this power.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:25:17', 'no', 'no', 0),
(211, 'Take for example&#44; disaster relief.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:27:05', 'no', 'no', 0),
(212, 'A well&#45;intentioned non&#45;profit could try to use Facebook to let refugees fleeing conflict know about safe places to go to for food and water. Now&#44; a group of human traffickers&#44; posing as well&#45;meaning citizens&#44; could do the same.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:28:14', 'no', 'no', 0),
(213, 'What kinds of resources will Facebook invest in verifying what&#39;s real versus fake?', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:28:45', 'no', 'no', 0),
(214, 'Zuckerberg&#39;s lofty goals require profound trust in his platform. And there are two industries – journalism and small advertisers – whose recent experiences with Facebook illustrate the dangers of over&#45;trusting.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:31:36', 'no', 'no', 0),
(215, 'Journalists have been surprised to learn that Facebook is concerned with driving engagement – not to be confused with civic engagement.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:33:24', 'no', 'no', 0),
(216, 'The algorithm that determines what you see in your Newsfeed prioritizes content that people want to share and comment on&#44; even if it&#39;s a lie.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:34:33', 'no', 'no', 0),
(217, 'Consider how fake news influenced the presidential campaign of 2016. One such story that went viral last fall claimed the Pope had endorsed Donald Trump.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:35:04', 'no', 'no', 0),
(218, 'If Facebook valued real journalism – where resources are poured into the expensive business of fact&#45;checking – its corporate leaders could have decided to implement a simple solution to fake news: make the source for news stories more prominent &#40;so I don&#39;t have to strain my eyes to see if it&#39;s the New York Times or the National Inquirer&#40;.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:37:55', 'no', 'no', 0),
(219, 'Facebook already does that for celebrities&#44; through the blue verification checkmark that tells you the platform has verified and confirmed the true identity of the person.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:39:43', 'no', 'no', 0),
(220, 'Imagine if Facebook had visually obvious verification for links that come from trusted news outlets. It would do an enormous public service. Facebook&#39;s current corporate approach to fact&#45;checking links is crowd&#45;sourcing. Let the users flag suspicious content.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:40:52', 'no', 'no', 0),
(221, 'It&#39;s a system susceptible to warring factions sabotaging each other. And it&#39;s not clear from the manifesto that Zuckerberg is willing to change the model to one that pays for essential human capital – far more expensive than software solutions.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:41:23', 'no', 'no', 0),
(222, 'Small advertisers have been discussed far less but probably have the best insight into Facebook&#39;s volatility as a platform. Say I decide to start a page for my tire shop on the site. For the first year&#44; I pay Facebook $5&#44;000 to advertise and the Facebook algorithm shows my posts to all my &#34;followers.&#34;', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:44:14', 'no', 'no', 0),
(223, 'But the next year&#44; the company decides to change the rules and say: for $5&#44;000 we will show your posts to 20% of fans. If you want to reach the same number you did last year&#44; you have to pay more.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:46:02', 'no', 'no', 0),
(224, 'These kinds of rule changes – some with dramatic financial implications – regularly occur on the platform. &#40;See for example this change last April that severely limited which users are allowed to post commercial content.&#40;', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:47:11', 'no', 'no', 0),
(225, 'They occur without a user vote and without a public comment period.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:47:42', 'no', 'no', 0),
(226, 'Right after CEO Zuckerberg posted his manifesto&#44; NPR emailed the company to ask about the new responsibilities that will come with the hoped&#45;for new power Facebook seeks.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:50:33', 'no', 'no', 0),
(227, 'If Facebook wants people to rely on the platform as the tool to build important social ties online&#44; what guarantees can Facebook give for its own accountability?', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:52:21', 'no', 'no', 0),
(228, 'Can it at least offer something as basic as a customer service hotline&#44; for example? Currently many users who are expelled without clear explanation or who have small business pages removed find it impossible to reach a human at the company for help.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:53:30', 'no', 'no', 0),
(229, 'A spokesperson did not answer the question&#44; and simply shared the company&#39;s press release summarizing Zuckerberg&#39;s points.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 11:54:01', 'no', 'no', 0),
(230, 'Norma McCorvey&#44; Roe Of Landmark &#39;Roe V. Wade&#39; Ruling On Abortion&#44; Dies At 69', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:01:49', 'no', 'no', 0),
(231, 'Many only know Norma McCorvey by a name that&#39;s not hers.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:02:58', 'no', 'no', 0),
(232, 'Under the pseudonym Jane Roe&#44; McCorvey became the central figure of Roe v. Wade&#44; the landmark 1973 Supreme Court ruling that legalized abortion in the U.S.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:03:29', 'no', 'no', 0),
(233, 'But in the decades that followed&#44; the complex woman came to serve as a champion at times for both sides of the deep divide over abortion rights.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:05:20', 'no', 'no', 0),
(234, 'McCorvey died Saturday of heart failure at the age of 69&#44; according to her daughter Melissa&#44; and Joshua Prager&#44; a journalist who is writing a book about the court case&#44; says McCorvey died in Katy&#44; Texas.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:08:08', 'no', 'no', 0),
(235, 'How McCorvey became Roe', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:08:51', 'no', 'no', 0),
(236, 'It was her third pregnancy &#45; after Melissa&#44; her eldest&#44; and another child McCorvey gave up for adoption — that brought McCorvey to the attention of the lawyers who would eventually take up her case.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:10:00', 'no', 'no', 0),
(237, 'The 22&#45;year&#45;old McCorvey&#44; who was then unmarried&#44; had been seeking an abortion but could not find a doctor in Texas who would perform the procedure&#44; which was then illegal except when the life of the mother was endangered.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:10:31', 'no', 'no', 0),
(238, 'Attorneys Sarah Weddington and Linda Coffee took up McCorvey&#39;s case&#44; and in 1970&#44; they filed the lawsuit that — after several twists and turns — would ultimately wind up at the Supreme Court.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:18:22', 'no', 'no', 0),
(239, 'By the time the ruling was finally passed down in 1973&#44; however&#44; McCorvey had already carried her pregnancy to term&#44; and had given the child up for adoption.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:21:10', 'no', 'no', 0),
(240, 'Though Roe v. Wade may not have changed McCorvey&#39;s particular circumstances&#44; the landmark Supreme Court ruling had a massive effect on the cultural and political landscape of the United States.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:21:53', 'no', 'no', 0),
(241, 'The 7&#45;2 decision&#44; which invalidated state bans on abortion in the U.S.&#44; may not have started the long&#45;simmering dispute over the procedure&#44; but it came to be its central flashpoint in the decades that followed.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:23:02', 'no', 'no', 0),
(242, 'McCorvey after the decision', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:23:33', 'no', 'no', 0),
(243, 'As Julie Rovner reported for NPR in 2013 — the decision&#39;s 40th anniversary — opinions on the ruling remained as deeply entrenched as the year it was handed down.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:25:24', 'no', 'no', 0);
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `body`, `added_by`, `user_to`, `date_added`, `user_closed`, `deleted`, `likes`) VALUES
(244, '&#34;Over the past two decades&#44; opinion on whether or not Roe should be overturned has barely changed&#44;&#34; Rovner reported at the time&#44; citing a Pew Research Center poll.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:28:12', 'no', 'no', 0),
(245, '&#34;In 1992&#44; 60 percent of those asked said the court should not overturn the ruling.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:28:55', 'no', 'no', 0),
(246, 'Today that&#39;s up to 63 percent.&#34;', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:30:04', 'no', 'no', 0),
(247, 'The case had no less of an impact later on McCorvey&#44; who was still just 25 when it ended. She maintained her anonymity for more than a decade&#44; until setting it aside in the 1980s.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:30:35', 'no', 'no', 0),
(248, 'At that point&#44; she remained a staunch defender of abortion rights&#44; &#34;working for a time at a Dallas women&#39;s clinic where abortions were performed&#44;&#34; according to The Associated Press.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:32:26', 'no', 'no', 0),
(249, 'Yet in the mid&#45;1990s&#44; after the publication of her first memoir&#44; McCorvey underwent a dramatic conversion — announcing that she had become a born&#45;again Christian.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:35:14', 'no', 'no', 0),
(250, 'What&#39;s more&#44; she went to work for the anti&#45;abortion group Operation Rescue&#44; from which position she then championed against the abortion rights granted by the case that bears her pseudonym.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:35:57', 'no', 'no', 0),
(251, '&#34;I&#39;ll be serving the Lord and helping women save their babies. I will hold a pro&#45;life position for the rest of my life&#44;&#34; McCorvey once said&#44; explaining her conversion.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:40:06', 'no', 'no', 0),
(252, '&#34;I think I&#39;ve always been pro&#45;life. I just didn&#39;t know it.&#34;', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:40:37', 'no', 'no', 0),
(253, 'In an interview with Fresh Air in the &#39;90s&#44; McCorvey looked back on her experience as Jane Roe.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:42:28', 'no', 'no', 0),
(254, '&#34;I feel like a role model in one sense of the word&#44;&#34; McCorvey said.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:48:16', 'no', 'no', 0),
(255, '&#34;But when people really stop and really sit down and think about Jane Roe or Norma McCorvey&#44; I feel like any woman who&#39;s ever been denied anything in her whole life is a Jane Roe.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:48:59', 'no', 'no', 0),
(256, 'Because no woman should have to suffer all the pain and humiliations and indignities that I&#39;ve had to face.&#34;', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 11:50:08', 'no', 'no', 0),
(257, 'A Thriving Rural Town&#39;s Winning Formula Faces New Threats Under Trump Administration', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:02:09', 'no', 'no', 0),
(258, 'The Finney County Courthouse is located in Garden City&#44; Kan. The thriving&#44; rural town has attracted people from across the globe to resettle there.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:02:52', 'no', 'no', 0),
(259, 'This is a two&#45;part story on immigrants and small town viability. Part one aired on this Weekend Edition Saturday. For the full story&#44; listen to both audio segments.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:04:01', 'no', 'no', 0),
(260, 'Like thousands of rural towns across the country&#44; Cawker City&#44; Kan.&#44; was built for bygone time.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:04:32', 'no', 'no', 0),
(261, 'Resident Linda Clover has spent most of her life in Cawker City&#44; and she loves the place&#44; but it&#39;s a shell of the town it used to be.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:05:23', 'no', 'no', 0),
(262, 'When I moved here in the &#39;60s we had three grocery stores&#44; she says. &#34;Now the number is zero.&#34;', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:06:00', 'no', 'no', 0),
(263, 'Cawker City has a common rural problem. When it formed&#44; 140 years ago&#44; the big families living on many small&#44; nearby farms had no other place to shop — or shoot pool.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:06:43', 'no', 'no', 0),
(264, 'Since then&#44; farms have grown much bigger&#44; the remaining families are smaller&#44; and increasingly they&#39;re doing much of their shopping online. As career opportunities in town dry up&#44; ambitious young adults tend to move away.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:07:52', 'no', 'no', 0),
(265, 'You have to find your little place in the world&#44; Linda Clover says. &#34;And we&#39;ve kind of lost it&#44; in our whole area really.&#34;', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:08:23', 'no', 'no', 0),
(266, 'But as some small towns struggle to remain viable&#44; others&#44; like Garden City&#44; Kan.&#44; are booming.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:09:14', 'no', 'no', 0),
(267, 'But&#44; other than being surrounded by cows and cornfields&#44; the town doesn&#39;t square with most people&#39;s stereotypes of rural Kansas.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:09:51', 'no', 'no', 0),
(268, 'Three&#44; 4 and 5&#45;year&#45;olds flock to their parents&#39; arms at a pre&#45;K school in Garden City.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:10:34', 'no', 'no', 0),
(269, 'Principal Josh Guymon says enrollment is up sharply since the start of the school year&#44; and these parents have come from all over the world.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:11:43', 'no', 'no', 0),
(270, 'We have a significant Burmese population&#44; Guymon says. &#34;We have a Vietnamese population.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:12:14', 'no', 'no', 0),
(271, 'We&#39;re seeing a lot of students come in from the northern African countries — Somalia&#44; Ethiopia — and of course&#44; the majority of them from Mexico or other countries in Central America.&#34;', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:13:05', 'no', 'no', 0),
(272, 'According to the latest census&#44; only about 40 percent of the residents here classify as &#34;white&#44; non&#45;Hispanic.&#34;', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:13:42', 'no', 'no', 0),
(273, 'Garden City is the most diverse community here in Kansas&#44; says Albert Kyaw&#44; a translator for the district&#44; who comes from Myanmar.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:14:25', 'no', 'no', 0),
(274, 'At least 27 different languages are spoken&#44; some say up to 40&#44; in a town of only 27&#44;000.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:15:34', 'no', 'no', 0),
(275, 'And these people are busy&#44; as unemployment hovers around 3 percent.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:16:05', 'no', 'no', 0),
(276, 'Parents pick up their kids from Garfield Early Childhood Center&#44; a pre&#45;K facility serving all children in the district.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:16:56', 'no', 'no', 0),
(277, 'Burmese&#44; Mandarin&#44; Arabic&#44; and many Spanish dialects are among at least 27 languages spoken at home by children in the district.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:17:33', 'no', 'no', 0),
(278, 'Frank Morris/KCUR', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:18:16', 'no', 'no', 0),
(279, 'City manager Matt Allen says it&#39;s an economic system powered by a steady stream of irrigated corn and immigrant labor.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:19:25', 'no', 'no', 0),
(280, 'In this region&#44; we pump water out of the ground to grow a tropical plant in the sand hills&#44; in mass&#44; so that we can feed cattle in mass&#44; so that we can kill cattle in mass&#44; so we can distribute beef in mass&#44; and that requires a big workforce&#44; he says. &#34;That is the common thread through the economy.&#34;', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:19:56', 'no', 'no', 0),
(281, 'All those workers&#44; producing food that the rest of the country buys&#44; bring wealth — in the form of stores&#44; services and terrific ethnic restaurants — to the remote western Kansas town.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:20:47', 'no', 'no', 0),
(282, 'All that&#44; in turn&#44; helps Garden City hang onto workers.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:21:24', 'no', 'no', 0),
(283, 'For us&#44; that matters. It&#39;s about workforce&#44; Allen says. &#34;It&#39;s about do we have enough fuel to run the engine.&#34;', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:22:07', 'no', 'no', 0),
(284, 'And Garden City&#39;s success is no accident.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:22:36', 'no', 'no', 0),
(285, 'The town&#39;s turning point came in the 1970s&#44; says Sister Janice Thome&#44; when city and church leaders debated bringing in a meatpacking plant.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:23:07', 'no', 'no', 0),
(286, 'Thome slides behind the wheel of her faded red Ford truck she uses to haul donated furniture to newcomers.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:23:58', 'no', 'no', 0),
(287, 'Those leaders&#44; as she recalls&#44; &#34;said&#44; if we say &#39;no&#44;&#39; then Garden City is liable to become one of these ghost towns&#44; like many other towns.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:24:35', 'no', 'no', 0),
(288, 'If we say yes&#44; then we&#39;ve got a vibrant economy&#44; but then we&#39;re going to be bringing all of&#44; quotes&#44; &#39;those people.&#39; &#34;', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:25:18', 'no', 'no', 0),
(289, 'Those people&#44; as in immigrants&#44; mostly poor ones&#44; who don&#39;t speak English&#44; and need significant help getting their footing in a new culture.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:25:47', 'no', 'no', 0),
(290, 'They decided they didn&#39;t want to be a ghost town&#44; so they would say yes&#44; and then they said&#44; &#39;OK&#44; are we going to count the people that come in then&#44; as a blessing or a curse?&#39;  Sister Thome says.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:26:18', 'no', 'no', 0),
(291, 'Farmers Are Courting Trump&#44; But They Don&#39;t Speak For All Of Rural America', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:27:09', 'no', 'no', 0),
(292, 'THE SALT', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:27:46', 'no', 'no', 0),
(293, 'Farmers Are Courting Trump&#44; But They Don&#39;t Speak For All Of Rural America', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:28:29', 'no', 'no', 0),
(294, 'Viewing them as a blessing won out. And after a lot of persistence&#44; effort and patience&#44; a pro&#45;immigrant ethos has gradually taken root here.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:28:58', 'no', 'no', 0),
(295, 'Ahmed Ali&#44; a spirited young Somali meat packer says he never wants to leave.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:29:29', 'no', 'no', 0),
(296, 'This town is so nice&#44; he says. &#34;The people in this town&#44; they are so great people. We love them&#44; and also they love us.&#34;', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:30:20', 'no', 'no', 0),
(297, 'In a way&#44; Garden City offers the same basic deal that settlers around here embraced in the late 1800s: Foreigners move to remote part of the country&#44; work hard and create a tight&#45;knit community to call home.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:30:57', 'no', 'no', 0),
(298, '3 Threats To A Successful Rural Town&#39;s Model', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:31:40', 'no', 'no', 0),
(299, 'But now&#44; Garden City&#39;s blueprint for success is under pressure from domestic terrorism&#44; and possibly from the Trump administration&#39;s focus on immigration.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:32:09', 'no', 'no', 0),
(300, 'In the town of many cultures&#44; one of its cultural hubs&#44; an African Somali shop&#44; lives in a metal building in a commercial strip near the outskirts of town.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:32:40', 'no', 'no', 0),
(301, 'Shelves overflow with bright African clothes and African food. In back there&#39;s a big TV playing African soccer&#44; some folding chairs and tables where guys like Marsal Maleye hang out after work.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:33:31', 'no', 'no', 0),
(302, 'Seven years&#44; in Kansas&#44; I&#39;ve never seen someone tell me&#44; &#39;Are you from Africa&#44; are you from this&#44; &#39; you just never&#44; Maleye says. &#34;And that&#39;s why I prefer Garden City be my house&#44; rest of my life.&#34;', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:34:08', 'no', 'no', 0),
(303, 'But Garden City&#39;s model — a vibrant economy built in a difficult environment by welcoming decades of immigrant labor — faces three distinct challenges.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:34:51', 'no', 'no', 0),
(304, 'One challenge cropped up earlier this month&#44; when immigrants did stop coming.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:35:20', 'no', 'no', 0),
(305, 'For me&#44; Garden City office in particular&#44; I don&#39;t have any scheduled arrival in the coming days or weeks&#44; says Amy Longa of the International Rescue Committee&#44; an agency that helps resettle refugees.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:35:51', 'no', 'no', 0),
(306, 'That&#39;s a problem because meatpacking&#44; the bedrock industry here&#44; is hard&#44; dirty work&#44; with high turnover.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:36:42', 'no', 'no', 0),
(307, 'With unemployment way below the national average&#44; Garden City&#39;s labor market is tight.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:37:19', 'no', 'no', 0),
(308, 'And Longa&#44; who came from Uganda a decade ago&#44; says refugees are motivated workers.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:38:02', 'no', 'no', 0),
(309, 'It&#39;s almost no plan B&#44; it&#39;s a plan A — you become an independent person&#44; and becoming independent is [being] able to pay your rent&#44; she says.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:38:31', 'no', 'no', 0),
(310, 'Immigrants working&#44; paying rent and taxes have turned Garden City and other meatpacking towns into islands of growth amid seas of rural decline.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:39:02', 'no', 'no', 0),
(311, 'And Garden City&#44; by and large&#44; welcomes and appreciates its immigrants&#44; as Carol Schieber found out when she was passing through&#44; from Guatemala&#44; 22 years ago.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:39:53', 'no', 'no', 0),
(312, 'It was so friendly and helpful&#44; she says. &#34;The people would greet you at the stores and help you as much as they could everywhere you went.&#34;', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:40:30', 'no', 'no', 0),
(313, 'Schieber liked the vibe here so much that she stayed.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:41:13', 'no', 'no', 0),
(314, 'Garden City is now majority Hispanic&#44; but the extremely diverse town still finds fresh ways to welcome newcomers.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:41:42', 'no', 'no', 0),
(315, 'Dr. John Birky moves a big medical exam table into a modest apartment&#44; with help from a couple of Somali men&#44; where he&#39;s setting up a non&#45;profit clinic handy for recent immigrants.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:42:13', 'no', 'no', 0),
(316, 'So&#44; this is actually going to be the waiting room. And then&#44; we&#39;ll come back here&#44; and so this will be one exam room&#44; you can see where they put a sink in there.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:43:04', 'no', 'no', 0),
(317, 'But he&#39;s aware of a second&#44; very serious menace to immigrants here.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:43:41', 'no', 'no', 0),
(318, 'Do we want to publicize this beyond the local community? Because we&#39;re always kind of asking ourselves&#44; what kind of bad actors are going to show up and cause issues&#44; Birky says.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:44:24', 'no', 'no', 0),
(319, 'In fact&#44; Garden City had a close brush with some alleged bad actors last fall&#44; when three men were charged with plotting a terrorist attack on a mosque and apartment complex in Garden City.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:44:33', 'no', 'no', 0),
(320, 'I got a little bit flashback&#44; says Ahmed Hassan Ali&#44; a Somali immigrant. &#34;I said&#44; &#39;Wow. What I was running from&#44; still is here.&#39; I never thought that&#44; really.&#34;', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:45:04', 'no', 'no', 0),
(321, 'He stands outside the low slung housing complex targeted by the bomb plot.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:45:55', 'no', 'no', 0),
(322, 'Ahmed Ali loves Garden City&#44; and tells everyone&#44; even people suggesting he go back to Africa&#44; that he&#39;s going to grow old there&#44; but the bomb plot gave him what he described as a flashback to the violence he left in Somalia.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:46:32', 'no', 'no', 0),
(323, 'There&#39;s a lot of families. Kids. Did nothing wrong. Away from civil wars&#44; problems back home&#44; Ali says.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:47:15', 'no', 'no', 0),
(324, 'They were seeking to have a better life in the United States.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:47:24', 'no', 'no', 0),
(325, 'Three members an anti&#45;Islamic militia calling itself the Crusaders allegedly prepared to set off bombs at the complex&#44; then to shoot any fleeing survivors.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:47:55', 'no', 'no', 0),
(326, 'Thanks to FBI&#44; thanks to law enforcement&#44; that didn&#39;t happen&#44; Ali says.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:48:46', 'no', 'no', 0),
(327, 'That&#39;s why we have a good connection with the law enforcement in Garden City&#44; especially Michael Utz&#44; he&#39;s a great guy.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:49:23', 'no', 'no', 0),
(328, 'When FBI agents told Garden City&#39;s chief of police&#44; Michael Utz&#44; about the bomb plot&#44; he reached out to the Muslim community.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:50:06', 'no', 'no', 0),
(329, 'To me&#44; it wasn&#39;t an attack on the Somalian population or the Burmese population&#44; this was an attack on our community&#44; Utz says.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:50:35', 'no', 'no', 0),
(330, 'Finney County Sheriff Kevin Bascue agrees. And he says there&#39;s a third problem vexing immigration here.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:51:06', 'no', 'no', 0),
(331, 'Another Trump administration executive order could force local law enforcement to check the immigration status of otherwise law&#45;abiding citizens.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:51:57', 'no', 'no', 0),
(332, 'I think that the threat to this community is the ending of what we&#39;ve worked so hard over many&#44; many years to happen here&#44; Bascue says.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:52:34', 'no', 'no', 0),
(333, 'The relationship built between police and the town&#39;s valued immigrant population.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:53:17', 'no', 'no', 0),
(334, 'I think our community would be a dying community without the immigrants that have come in to fill in the gaps&#44; and to grow business&#44; he adds.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:53:46', 'no', 'no', 0),
(335, 'Bascue says the district&#39;s law enforcement will continue to cooperate fully with federal Immigration agents&#44; but with an eye toward preserving Garden City&#39;s winning formula — which starts with immigrants.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 11:54:17', 'no', 'no', 0),
(336, 'Isaac Newton', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:04:53', 'no', 'no', 0),
(337, 'Early Life', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:05:56', 'no', 'no', 0),
(338, 'On January 4&#44; 1643&#44; Isaac Newton was born in the hamlet of Woolsthorpe&#44; Lincolnshire&#44; England (using the &#34;old&#34; Julien calendar&#44; Newton&#39;s birth date is sometimes displayed as December 25&#44; 1642). He was the only son of a prosperous local farmer&#44; also named Isaac Newton&#44; who died three months before he was born. A premature baby born tiny and weak&#44; Newton was not expected to survive.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:06:39', 'no', 'no', 0),
(339, 'When he was 3 years old&#44; his mother&#44; Hannah Ayscough Newton&#44; remarried a well&#45;to&#45;do minister&#44; Barnabas Smith&#44; and went to live with him&#44; leaving young Newton with his maternal grandmother. The experience left an indelible imprint on Newton&#44; later manifesting itself as an acute sense of insecurity. He anxiously obsessed over his published work&#44; defending its merits with irrational behavior.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:08:16', 'no', 'no', 0),
(340, 'At age 12&#44; Newton was reunited with his mother after her second husband died. She brought along her three small children from her second marriage. Newton had been enrolled at the King&#39;s School in Grantham&#44; a town in Lincolnshire&#44; where he lodged with a local apothecary and was introduced to the fascinating world of chemistry.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:09:30', 'no', 'no', 0),
(341, 'His mother pulled him out of school&#44; for her plan was to make him a farmer and have him tend the farm.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:10:47', 'no', 'no', 0),
(342, 'Newton failed miserably&#44; as he found farming monotonous.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:11:50', 'no', 'no', 0),
(343, 'He soon was sent back to King&#39;s School to finish his basic education. Perhaps sensing the young man&#39;s innate intellectual abilities&#44; his uncle&#44; a graduate of the University of Cambridge&#39;s Trinity College&#44; persuaded Newton&#39;s mother to have him enter the university. Newton enrolled in a program similar to a work&#45;study in 1661&#44; and subsequently waited on tables and took care of wealthier students&#39; rooms.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:12:33', 'no', 'no', 0),
(344, 'When Newton arrived at Cambridge&#44; the Scientific Revolution of the 17th century was already in full force. The heliocentric view of the universe—theorized by astronomers Nicolaus Copernicus and Johannes Kepler&#44; and later refined by Galileo—was well known in most European academic circles. Philosopher René Descartes had begun to formulate a new concept of nature as an intricate&#44; impersonal and inert machine.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:14:10', 'no', 'no', 0),
(345, 'Yet&#44; like most universities in Europe&#44; Cambridge was steeped in Aristotelian philosophy and a view of nature resting on a geocentric view of the universe&#44; dealing with nature in qualitative rather than quantitative terms.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:15:24', 'no', 'no', 0),
(346, 'During his first three years at Cambridge&#44; Newton was taught the standard curriculum but was fascinated with the more advanced science. All his spare time was spent reading from the modern philosophers. The result was a less&#45;than&#45;stellar performance&#44; but one that is understandable&#44; given his dual course of study.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:16:41', 'no', 'no', 0),
(347, 'It was during this time that Newton kept a second set of notes&#44; entitled &#34;Quaestiones Quaedam Philosophicae&#34; (&#34;Certain Philosophical Questions&#34;). The &#34;Quaestiones&#34; reveal that Newton had discovered the new concept of nature that provided the framework for the Scientific Revolution.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:17:44', 'no', 'no', 0),
(348, 'Though Newton graduated with no honors or distinctions&#44; his efforts won him the title of scholar and four years of financial support for future education. Unfortunately&#44; in 1665&#44; the Great Plague that was ravaging Europe had come to Cambridge&#44; forcing the university to close. Newton returned home to pursue his private study.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:18:27', 'no', 'no', 0),
(349, 'It was during this 18&#45;month hiatus that he conceived the method of infinitesimal calculus&#44; set foundations for his theory of light and color&#44; and gained significant insight into the laws of planetary motion—insights that eventually led to the publication of his Principia in 1687. Legend has it that&#44; at this time&#44; Newton experienced his famous inspiration of gravity with the falling apple.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:20:04', 'no', 'no', 0),
(350, 'When the threat of plague subsided in 1667&#44; Newton returned to Cambridge and was elected a minor fellow at Trinity College&#44; as he was still not considered a standout scholar. However&#44; in the ensuing years&#44; his fortune improved. Newton received his Master of Arts degree in 1669&#44; before he was 27. During this time&#44; he came across Nicholas Mercator&#39;s published book on methods for dealing with infinite series.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:21:18', 'no', 'no', 0),
(351, 'Newton quickly wrote a treatise&#44; De Analysi&#44; expounding his own wider&#45;ranging results. He shared this with friend and mentor Isaac Barrow&#44; but didn&#39;t include his name as author.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:22:35', 'no', 'no', 0),
(352, 'In June 1669&#44; Barrow shared the unaccredited manuscript with British mathematician John Collins. In August 1669&#44; Barrow identified its author to Collins as &#34;Mr. Newton ... very young ... but of an extraordinary genius and proficiency in these things.&#34;', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:23:38', 'no', 'no', 0),
(353, 'Newton&#39;s work was brought to the attention of the mathematics community for the first time.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:24:21', 'no', 'no', 0),
(354, 'Shortly afterward&#44; Barrow resigned his Lucasian professorship at Cambridge&#44; and Newton assumed the chair.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:25:58', 'no', 'no', 0),
(355, 'Professional Life', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:27:12', 'no', 'no', 0),
(356, 'As a professor&#44; Newton was exempted from tutoring but required to deliver an annual course of lectures. He chose to deliver his work on optics as his initial topic. Part of Newton&#39;s study of optics was aided with the use of a reflecting telescope that he designed and constructed in 1668—his first major public scientific achievement. This invention helped prove his theory of light and color.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:28:29', 'no', 'no', 0),
(357, 'The Royal Society asked for a demonstration of his reflecting telescope in 1671&#44; and the organization&#39;s interest encouraged Newton to publish his notes on light&#44; optics and color in 1672; these notes were later published as part of Newton&#39;s Opticks: Or&#44; A treatise of the Reflections&#44; Refractions&#44; Inflections and Colours of Light.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:29:32', 'no', 'no', 0),
(358, 'However&#44; not everyone at the Royal Academy was enthusiastic about Newton&#39;s discoveries in optics. Among the dissenters was Robert Hooke&#44; one of the original members of the Royal Academy and a scientist who was accomplished in a number of areas&#44; including mechanics and optics. In his paper&#44; Newton theorized that white light was a composite of all colors of the spectrum&#44; and that light was composed of particles.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:30:15', 'no', 'no', 0),
(359, 'Hooke believed that light was composed of waves. Hooke quickly condemned Newton&#39;s paper in condescending terms&#44; and attacked Newton&#39;s methodology and conclusions.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:31:52', 'no', 'no', 0),
(360, 'Hooke was not the only one to question Newton&#39;s work in optics. Renowned Dutch scientist Christiaan Huygens and a number of French Jesuits also raised objections. But because of Hooke&#39;s association with the Royal Society and his own work in optics&#44; his criticism stung Newton the worst. Unable to handle the critique&#44; he went into a rage—a reaction to criticism that was to continue throughout his life.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:33:06', 'no', 'no', 0),
(361, 'Newton denied Hooke&#39;s charge that his theories had any shortcomings&#44; and argued the importance of his discoveries to all of science. In the ensuing months&#44; the exchange between the two men grew more acrimonious&#44; and soon Newton threatened to quit the society altogether. He remained only when several other members assured him that the Fellows held him in high esteem.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:34:23', 'no', 'no', 0),
(362, 'However&#44; the rivalry between Newton and Hooke would continue for several years thereafter. Then&#44; in 1678&#44; Newton suffered a complete nervous breakdown and the correspondence abruptly ended. The death of his mother the following year caused him to become even more isolated&#44; and for six years he withdrew from intellectual exchange except when others initiated correspondence&#44; which he always kept short.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:35:26', 'no', 'no', 0),
(363, 'During his hiatus from public life&#44; Newton returned to his study of gravitation and its effects on the orbits of planets. Ironically&#44; the impetus that put Newton on the right direction in this study came from Robert Hooke.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:36:09', 'no', 'no', 0),
(364, 'In a 1679 letter of general correspondence to Royal Society members for contributions&#44; Hooke wrote to Newton and brought up the question of planetary motion&#44; suggesting that a formula involving the inverse squares might explain the attraction between planets and the shape of their orbits.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:37:46', 'no', 'no', 0),
(365, 'Subsequent exchanges transpired before Newton quickly broke off the correspondence once again. But Hooke&#39;s idea was soon incorporated into Newton&#39;s work on planetary motion&#44; and from his notes it appears he had quickly drawn his own conclusions by 1680&#44; though he kept his discoveries to himself.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:39:00', 'no', 'no', 0),
(366, 'In early 1684&#44; in a conversation with fellow Royal Society members Christopher Wren and Edmond Halley&#44; Hooke made his case on the proof for planetary motion. Both Wren and Halley thought he was on to something&#44; but pointed out that a mathematical demonstration was needed. In August 1684&#44; Halley traveled to Cambridge to visit with Newton&#44; who was coming out of his seclusion.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:40:17', 'no', 'no', 0),
(367, 'Halley idly asked him what shape the orbit of a planet would take if its attraction to the sun followed the inverse square of the distance between them (Hooke&#39;s theory).', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:41:20', 'no', 'no', 0),
(368, 'Newton knew the answer&#44; due to his concentrated work for the past six years&#44; and replied&#44; &#34;An ellipse.&#34; Newton claimed to have solved the problem some 18 years prior&#44; during his hiatus from Cambridge and the plague&#44; but he was unable to find his notes. Halley persuaded him to work out the problem mathematically and offered to pay all costs so that the ideas might be published.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:42:03', 'no', 'no', 0),
(369, 'Srinivasa Ramanujan', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:01:49', 'no', 'no', 0),
(370, 'Indian mathematician', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:03:03', 'no', 'no', 0),
(371, 'Srinivasa Ramanujan&#44; (born December 22&#44; 1887&#44; Erode&#44; India—died April 26&#44; 1920&#44; Kumbakonam)&#44; Indian mathematician whose contributions to the theory of numbers include pioneering discoveries of the properties of the partition function.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:04:20', 'no', 'no', 0),
(372, 'When he was 15 years old&#44; he obtained a copy of George Shoobridge Carr’s Synopsis of Elementary Results in Pure and Applied Mathematics&#44; 2 vol. (1880–86). This collection of thousands of theorems&#44; many presented with only the briefest of proofs and with no material newer than 1860&#44; aroused his genius.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:05:23', 'no', 'no', 0),
(373, 'Having verified the results in Carr’s book&#44; Ramanujan went beyond it&#44; developing his own theorems and ideas.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:06:06', 'no', 'no', 0),
(374, 'In 1903 he secured a scholarship to the University of Madras but lost it the following year because he neglected all other studies in pursuit of mathematics.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:07:43', 'no', 'no', 0),
(375, 'Ramanujan continued his work&#44; without employment and living in the poorest circumstances.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:08:57', 'no', 'no', 0),
(376, 'After marrying in 1909 he began a search for permanent employment that culminated in an interview with a government official&#44; Ramachandra Rao.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:10:14', 'no', 'no', 0),
(377, 'Impressed by Ramanujan’s mathematical prowess&#44; Rao supported his research for a time&#44; but Ramanujan&#44; unwilling to exist on charity&#44; obtained a clerical post with the Madras Port Trust.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:11:17', 'no', 'no', 0),
(378, 'In 1911 Ramanujan published the first of his papers in the Journal of the Indian Mathematical Society.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:12:00', 'no', 'no', 0),
(379, 'His genius slowly gained recognition&#44; and in 1913 he began a correspondence with the British mathematician Godfrey H. Hardy that led to a special scholarship from the University of Madras and a grant from Trinity College&#44; Cambridge.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:13:37', 'no', 'no', 0),
(380, 'Overcoming his religious objections&#44; Ramanujan traveled to England in 1914&#44; where Hardy tutored him and collaborated with him in some research.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:14:51', 'no', 'no', 0),
(381, 'Ramanujan’s knowledge of mathematics (most of which he had worked out for himself) was startling.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:16:08', 'no', 'no', 0),
(382, 'Although he was almost completely unaware of modern developments in mathematics&#44; his mastery of continued fractions was unequaled by any living mathematician.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:17:11', 'no', 'no', 0),
(383, 'He worked out the Riemann series&#44; the elliptic integrals&#44; hypergeometric series&#44; the functional equations of the zeta function&#44; and his own theory of divergent series.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:17:54', 'no', 'no', 0),
(384, 'On the other hand&#44; he knew nothing of doubly periodic functions&#44; the classical theory of quadratic forms&#44; or Cauchy’s theorem&#44; and he had only the most nebulous idea of what constitutes a mathematical proof.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:19:31', 'no', 'no', 0),
(385, 'Though brilliant&#44; many of his theorems on the theory of prime numbers were wrong.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:20:45', 'no', 'no', 0),
(386, 'In England Ramanujan made further advances&#44; especially in the partition of numbers (the number of ways that a positive integer can be expressed as the sum of positive integers; e.g.&#44; 4 can be expressed as 4&#44; 3 + 1&#44; 2 + 2&#44; 2 + 1 + 1&#44; and 1 + 1 + 1 + 1).', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:22:02', 'no', 'no', 0),
(387, 'His papers were published in English and European journals&#44; and in 1918 he was elected to the Royal Society of London.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:23:05', 'no', 'no', 0),
(388, 'In 1917 Ramanujan had contracted tuberculosis&#44; but his condition improved sufficiently for him to return to India in 1919.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:23:48', 'no', 'no', 0),
(389, 'He died the following year&#44; generally unknown to the world at large but recognized by mathematicians as a phenomenal genius&#44; without peer since Leonhard Euler (1707–83) and Carl Jacobi (1804–51).', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:25:25', 'no', 'no', 0),
(390, 'Ramanujan left behind three notebooks and a sheaf of pages (also called the “lost notebook”) containing many unpublished results that mathematicians continued to verify long after his death.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:26:39', 'no', 'no', 0),
(391, 'Prime number theorem', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:27:56', 'no', 'no', 0),
(392, 'One of the supreme achievements of 19th&#45;century mathematics was the prime number theorem&#44; and it is worth a brief digression.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:28:59', 'no', 'no', 0),
(393, 'To begin&#44; designate the number of primes less than or equal to n by &#960;(n).', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:29:42', 'no', 'no', 0),
(394, 'Thus &#960;(10) = 4 because 2&#44; 3&#44; 5&#44; and 7 are the four primes not exceeding 10.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:31:19', 'no', 'no', 0),
(395, 'Similarly &#960;(25) = 9 and &#960;(100) = 25.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:32:33', 'no', 'no', 0),
(396, 'Next&#44; consider the proportion of numbers less than or equal to n that are prime—i.e.&#44; &#960;(n)/n.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:33:50', 'no', 'no', 0),
(397, 'Clearly (10)/10 = 0.40&#44; meaning that 40 percent of the numbers not exceeding 10 are prime.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:34:53', 'no', 'no', 0),
(398, 'A pattern is anything but clear&#44; but the prime number theorem identifies one&#44; at least approximately&#44; and thereby provides a rule for the distribution of primes among the whole numbers.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:35:36', 'no', 'no', 0),
(399, 'The theorem says that&#44; for large n&#44; the proportion &#960;(n)/n is roughly 1/log n&#44; where log n is the natural logarithm of n.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:37:13', 'no', 'no', 0),
(400, 'This link between primes and logs is nothing short of extraordinary.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:38:27', 'no', 'no', 0),
(401, 'One of the first to perceive this was the young Gauss&#44; whose examination of log tables and prime numbers suggested it to his fertile mind.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:39:44', 'no', 'no', 0),
(402, 'Following Dirichlet’s exploitation of analytic techniques in number theory&#44; Bernhard Riemann (1826–66) and Pafnuty Chebyshev (1821–94) made substantial progress before the prime number theorem was proved in 1896 by Jacques Hadamard (1865–1963) and Charles Jean de la Vallée&#45;Poussin (1866–1962).', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:40:47', 'no', 'no', 0),
(403, 'This brought the 19th century to a triumphant close.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:41:30', 'no', 'no', 0),
(404, 'Benjamin Banneker', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:04:01', 'no', 'no', 0),
(405, 'Astronomer&#44; Scientist (1731–1806)', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:05:15', 'no', 'no', 0),
(406, 'Benjamin Banneker was a largely self&#45;educated mathematician&#44; astronomer&#44; compiler of almanacs and writer.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:07:32', 'no', 'no', 0),
(407, 'The colour of the skin is in no way connected with strength of the mind or intellectual powers. —Benjamin Banneker', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:08:35', 'no', 'no', 0),
(408, 'Benjamin Banneker was born on November 9&#44; 1731&#44; in Ellicott&#39;s Mills&#44; Maryland.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:09:18', 'no', 'no', 0),
(409, 'A free black man who owned a farm near Baltimore&#44; Banneker was largely self&#45;educated in astronomy and mathematics.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:10:55', 'no', 'no', 0),
(410, 'He was later called upon to assist in the surveying of territory for the construction of the nation&#39;s capital.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:12:09', 'no', 'no', 0),
(411, 'He also became an active writer of almanacs and exchanged letters with Thomas Jefferson&#44; politely challenging him to do what he could to ensure racial equality.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:14:26', 'no', 'no', 0),
(412, 'Banneker died on October 9&#44; 1806.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:15:29', 'no', 'no', 0),
(413, 'Background and Early Years', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:16:12', 'no', 'no', 0),
(414, 'Born on November 9&#44; 1731&#44; in Ellicott&#39;s Mills&#44; Maryland&#44; Benjamin Banneker was the son of an ex&#45;slave named Robert and his wife&#44; Mary Banneky.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:17:49', 'no', 'no', 0),
(415, 'Mary was the daughter of an Englishwoman named Molly Welsh&#44; a former indentured servant&#44; and her husband&#44; Bannka&#44; an ex&#45;slave whom she freed and who asserted that he came from tribal royalty in West Africa.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:19:03', 'no', 'no', 0),
(416, 'Because both of his parents were free&#44; Benjamin escaped the wrath of slavery as well.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:21:20', 'no', 'no', 0),
(417, 'He was taught to read by his maternal grandmother and for a very short time attended a small Quaker school.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:23:37', 'no', 'no', 0),
(418, 'Banneker was primarily self&#45;educated&#44; a fact that did little to diminish his brilliance.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:25:54', 'no', 'no', 0),
(419, 'His early accomplishments included constructing an irrigation system for the family farm and a wooden clock that was reputed to keep accurate time and ran for more than 50 years until his death. In addition&#44; Banneker taught himself astronomy and accurately forecasted lunar and solar eclipses.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:27:31', 'no', 'no', 0),
(420, 'After his father&#39;s passing&#44; he ran his own farm for years&#44; cultivating a business selling tobacco via crops.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:28:45', 'no', 'no', 0),
(421, 'Interests in Astronomy and Surveying', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:31:02', 'no', 'no', 0),
(422, 'Banneker&#39;s talents and intelligence eventually came to the attention of the Ellicott family&#44; entrepreneurs who had made a name and fortune by building a series of gristmills in the Baltimore area in the 1770s.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:32:05', 'no', 'no', 0),
(423, 'George Ellicott had a large personal library and loaned Banneker numerous books on astronomy and other fields.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:32:48', 'no', 'no', 0),
(424, 'In 1791&#44; Andrew Ellicott&#44; George’s cousin&#44; hired Banneker to assist in surveying territory for the nation’s capital city.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:34:25', 'no', 'no', 0),
(425, 'He worked in the observatory tent using a zenith sector to record the movement of the stars.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:36:42', 'no', 'no', 0),
(426, 'However&#44; due to a sudden illness&#44; Banneker was only able to work for Ellicott for about three months.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:37:59', 'no', 'no', 0),
(427, 'Popular Almanacs', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:39:02', 'no', 'no', 0),
(428, 'Banneker&#39;s true acclaim&#44; however&#44; came from his almanacs&#44; which he published for six consecutive years during the later years of his life&#44; between 1792 and 1797.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:39:45', 'no', 'no', 0),
(429, 'These handbooks included his own astronomical calculations as well as opinion pieces&#44; literature and medical and tidal information&#44; with the latter particularly useful to fishermen.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:41:22', 'no', 'no', 0),
(430, 'Outside of his almanacs&#44; Banneker also published information on bees and calculated the cycle of the 17&#45;year locust.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:43:39', 'no', 'no', 0),
(431, 'Senator Tom Harkin delivers third annual Living Constitution Lecture', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:09:37', 'no', 'no', 0),
(432, 'On June 14&#44; Iowa Senator Tom Harkin delivered the Brennan Center for Justice&#39;s third annual Living Constitution Lecture.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:10:40', 'no', 'no', 0),
(433, 'A long time activist for filibuster reform&#44; Harkin discussed his proposal to address a problem that he says has left Congress unable to function effectively.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:11:23', 'no', 'no', 0),
(434, '[Watch Senator Harkin&#39;s lecture at the Brennan Center&#39;s Web site.] http://www.brennancenter.org/content/pages/2010_living_constitution_lecture', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:13:00', 'no', 'no', 0),
(435, 'The filibuster&#44; initiated in the U.S. Senate ostensibly for protecting the minority party and allowing for debate of potential bills&#44; has become a tactic used by senators to delay Senate voting&#44; said Harkin. Under current Senate rules&#44; a motion for cloture—a call to end floor debate—requires 60 votes.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:15:17', 'no', 'no', 0),
(436, 'The result is that even when 51 senators are ready to approve a bill&#44; they can only end a filibuster if they have a &#34;super&#45;majority&#34; of 60 votes.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:16:34', 'no', 'no', 0),
(437, 'The abuse of these technicalities&#44; Harkin says&#44; has led to a spike in the use of the filibuster: an average of one bill was filibustered each congressional term in the 1950s; in the 2007&#45;2008 term cloture votes were called 139 times.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:17:37', 'no', 'no', 0),
(438, 'The result&#44; said Harkin&#44; is that the Senate is unable to operate effectively.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:18:20', 'no', 'no', 0),
(439, 'There are about 300 bills now that have been passed by the House that are just sitting at the doorstep of the Senate&#44; that we can&#39;t take up&#44; Harkin said.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:19:57', 'no', 'no', 0),
(440, 'The delays have especially affected President Barrack Obama&#39;s administrative and judicial nominations: according to Harkin&#44; over 100 Obama nominees are awaiting confirmation. At the same juncture in President George W. Bush&#39;s first term&#44; only eight nominees remained unconfirmed.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:22:14', 'no', 'no', 0),
(441, 'Under Harkin&#39;s proposal&#44; filibusters would be curbed by constraining the time allowed for floor debate.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:23:31', 'no', 'no', 0),
(442, 'In the example given by Harkin&#44; a cloture vote would still initially require 60 votes.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:24:34', 'no', 'no', 0),
(443, 'Then&#44; after allowing for two more days of debate&#44; cloture would require 57 votes.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:25:17', 'no', 'no', 0),
(444, 'After another two days&#44; just 54 would be needed&#44; and eventually 51.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:26:54', 'no', 'no', 0),
(445, 'A determined minority could slow down any bill for as much as eight days&#44; said Harkin.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:29:11', 'no', 'no', 0),
(446, '&#34;Senators would have ample time to make their arguments and attempt to persuade the public and the majority of their colleagues.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:30:28', 'no', 'no', 0),
(447, 'I think this protects the rights of the minority to full and vigorous debate and deliberation&#44; maintaining the very best features of the U.S. Senate.&#34;', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:31:31', 'no', 'no', 0),
(448, 'The Living Constitution Lecture is part of the Brennan Center&#39;s Living Constitution Project&#44; which was initiated to spark debate and shape conversation amongst thinkers and policymakers and promote a progressive interpretation of the Constitution.', 'al_nolan', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:32:14', 'no', 'no', 0),
(449, 'Lesson 1: The Declaration of Independence', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 10:03:41', 'no', 'no', 0),
(450, 'Thomas Jefferson wrote most of the Declaration of Independence in the early summer of 1776.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 10:04:42', 'no', 'no', 0),
(451, 'Its purpose was to announce that the 13 English colonies in North America had decided to become independent of England and start their own&#44; new country.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 10:07:33', 'no', 'no', 0),
(452, 'Jefferson used ideas about people and governments that were new in the 1600s and 1700s.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 10:08:34', 'no', 'no', 0),
(453, 'One important idea stated in the Declaration of Independence was that &#34;all men are created equal.&#34;', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 10:11:35', 'no', 'no', 0),
(454, 'Jefferson  wrote that God gave rights to people&#45;&#45; &#34;Life&#44; Liberty&#44; and the pursuit of Happiness&#34;&#45;&#45; and that no one or no government should be able to take those rights away.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 10:14:26', 'no', 'no', 0),
(455, 'Another idea is that a government gets its power from the people.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 10:15:27', 'no', 'no', 0),
(456, 'This principle is called popular sovereignty.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 10:17:18', 'no', 'no', 0),
(457, 'The Declaration of Independence states that a government gets or derives its power from the people it rules.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 10:18:19', 'no', 'no', 0),
(458, 'If the government misuses its power&#44; the people have the right to form a new government. ', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 10:19:20', 'no', 'no', 0),
(459, 'By the middle of the 1700s&#44; English colonists living in America had set up their own governments in towns and colonies.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 10:22:21', 'no', 'no', 0),
(460, 'They usually made their own laws and chose the people they wanted to represent them.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 10:25:12', 'no', 'no', 0),
(461, 'In 1760&#44; King George III became the ruler of Great Britain and decided to take more control of the colonies.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 10:28:03', 'no', 'no', 0),
(462, 'King George and the English Parliament passed taxes and laws that the colonists hated and felt were unfair.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 10:30:54', 'no', 'no', 0),
(463, 'In 1774&#44; a group of colonial leaders met &#40;the First Continental Congress&#41; and wrote a letter to the king declaring they were loyal subjects and asking him to let them elect their own leaders and make their own laws.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 10:33:55', 'no', 'no', 0),
(464, 'King George ignored the colonists&#39; complaints and said the colonies were in rebellion. ', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 10:34:56', 'no', 'no', 0),
(465, 'The colonists felt that England and the king had abused their power.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 10:35:57', 'no', 'no', 0);
INSERT INTO `posts` (`id`, `body`, `added_by`, `user_to`, `date_added`, `user_closed`, `deleted`, `likes`) VALUES
(466, 'And as the Declaration of Independence states&#44; when this happens to people&#44; &#34;It is their right&#44; their duty&#44; to throw off such Government.&#34; ', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 10:39:58', 'no', 'no', 0),
(467, 'The signing of the Declaration of Independence', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 10:43:59', 'no', 'no', 0),
(468, 'Each of the 13 colonies sent representatives to a meeting in Philadelphia&#44; called the Second Continental Congress.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 10:45:00', 'no', 'no', 0),
(469, 'On July 4&#44; 1776&#44; these 56 delegates signed and adopted the Declaration of Independence.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 10:47:51', 'no', 'no', 0),
(470, 'Lesson 2:  Introduction to the U.S. Constitution', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:03:41', 'no', 'no', 0),
(471, 'The U.S. Constitution states basic principles which guide our country&#39;s government and  laws.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:04:42', 'no', 'no', 0),
(472, 'When it was written in 1787&#44;  it was the plan which told the beginning country  how to form its  government.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:05:13', 'no', 'no', 0),
(473, 'For example&#44; the Constitution said that the United States would have a president and a vice president.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:08:50', 'no', 'no', 0),
(474, 'The Constitution  also said that people would elect other people to represent them.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:11:21', 'no', 'no', 0),
(475, 'These elected representatives would form a Congress.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:11:52', 'no', 'no', 0),
(476, 'The Constitution also guarantees the rights and liberties of the American people&#44; such as freedom of speech and freedom of religion.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:12:23', 'no', 'no', 0),
(477, 'Today&#44; the Constitution remains the most important guide to all parts of government.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:13:24', 'no', 'no', 0),
(478, 'It is often called the &#34;highest law of the land.&#34; This means that no state&#44; no branch of government&#44; no person&#44; no elected official&#45;&#45;not even the president or Congress&#45;&#45;can make a law or enforce a condition that goes against the Constitution.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:13:55', 'no', 'no', 0),
(479, 'The Constitution continues to protect the rights and freedoms of American citizens. ', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:17:32', 'no', 'no', 0),
(480, 'Principles and Powers', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:20:03', 'no', 'no', 0),
(481, 'The first principle is that government is created by and gets its power from the people.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:20:34', 'no', 'no', 0),
(482, 'This idea is called popular sovereignty.  The Declaration of Independence had stated this idea clearly when it said: &#34;Governments are instituted among Men&#44; deriving their just powers from the consent of the governed.&#34;     ', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:21:05', 'no', 'no', 0),
(483, '&#34;We the People&#34; are the first words of the Constitution and are written larger than any thing else.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:22:06', 'no', 'no', 0),
(484, 'The writers wanted to emphasize that the ability to set up and start a new government came from the people of the United States.  ', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:22:37', 'no', 'no', 0),
(485, 'A second principle is federalism.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:26:14', 'no', 'no', 0),
(486, 'The Constitution divides power&#44; giving some power to the central or national government and some power to state governments. The Constitution lists things the national or federal government can do; these are delegated powers.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:28:45', 'no', 'no', 0),
(487, 'The Constitution lists things which the national government and the state governments cannot do. Some powers&#44; like collecting taxes&#44; are concurrent&#44; powers that both the national and state governments can exercise.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:29:16', 'no', 'no', 0),
(488, 'The chart below gives some examples. ', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:29:47', 'no', 'no', 0),
(489, 'National powers: declare war&#44; handle foreign affairs&#44; print money', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:30:48', 'no', 'no', 0),
(490, 'Concurrent powers: collect taxes&#44; create courts&#44; make marriage laws', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:31:19', 'no', 'no', 0),
(491, 'State powers: punish criminals&#44; set up schools&#44; create county and city governments', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:34:56', 'no', 'no', 0),
(492, 'The Constitution doesn&#39;t list all the powers of the states.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:37:27', 'no', 'no', 0),
(493, 'Article 1 prohibits or forbids the states to do certain things such as make its own money&#44; declare war on another country&#44; or make treaties with another country.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:37:58', 'no', 'no', 0),
(494, 'Amendment 10 of the Constitution then states that powers not given to the national government and not forbidden to the states are reserved to the states. ', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:38:29', 'no', 'no', 0),
(495, 'Another main idea or principle in the Constitution is separation of powers.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:39:30', 'no', 'no', 0),
(496, 'The first three Articles divide the national government  into three branches:  legislative&#44; executive&#44; and judicial.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:40:01', 'no', 'no', 0),
(497, 'The writers of the Constitution did not want one part of government to become too powerful.      ', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:43:38', 'no', 'no', 0),
(498, 'In addition to dividing power into three branches&#44; the writers were careful to add checks and balances  to the Constitution.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:46:09', 'no', 'no', 0),
(499, 'Each branch of government has some limits placed on it by another branch.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:46:40', 'no', 'no', 0),
(500, 'For example&#44; Congress&#45;&#45;the legislative branch&#45;&#45; makes all laws.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:47:11', 'no', 'no', 0),
(501, 'But Congress can&#39;t make laws which go against the Constitution&#44; and the Supreme Court&#45;&#45;the judicial branch&#45;&#45; can declare a law unconstitutional.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 10:48:12', 'no', 'no', 0),
(502, 'Writing the Constitution', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:03:41', 'no', 'no', 0),
(503, 'Independence Hall Philadelphia&#44; Pennsylvania', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:04:42', 'no', 'no', 0),
(504, 'In 1787&#44; delegates met in Independence Hall to rewrite the Articles of Confederation.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:05:13', 'no', 'no', 0),
(505, 'The Articles of Confederation&#44; written after the Declaration of Independence&#44; were a first attempt at designing a government for the new country.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:06:01', 'no', 'no', 0),
(506, 'But by 1787&#44; it was obvious that the Articles of Confederation were not working and many changes were needed. ', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:07:29', 'no', 'no', 0),
(507, 'Delegates from 12 of the 13 states came to Philadelphia in May 1787&#44; but many of the 55 delegates who came were not happy.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:08:30', 'no', 'no', 0),
(508, 'Most delegates felt strongly loyal to the states they represented and were opposed to writing a constitution which created a strong national government.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:09:01', 'no', 'no', 0),
(509, 'However&#44;  two delegates&#44; James Madison and Alexander Hamilton&#44; were convinced that the new country needed a strong&#44; central government.  ', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:09:49', 'no', 'no', 0),
(510, 'The 55 delegates were strong&#45;willed&#44; successful people.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:11:17', 'no', 'no', 0),
(511, 'Most delegates were important in their state governments.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:12:18', 'no', 'no', 0),
(512, 'Many had fought in the American Revolution.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:12:49', 'no', 'no', 0),
(513, 'Thomas Jefferson did not come&#44; but 8 people who had signed the Declaration of Independence were there.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:13:37', 'no', 'no', 0),
(514, 'All delegates agreed that George Washington should be president of the convention.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:15:05', 'no', 'no', 0),
(515, 'Benjamin Franklin&#44; at age 81&#44; was the oldest delegate.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:16:06', 'no', 'no', 0),
(516, 'Delegates disagreed and became angry with one another.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:16:37', 'no', 'no', 0),
(517, 'The summer of 1787 was one of the hottest ever in Philadelphia.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:17:25', 'no', 'no', 0),
(518, 'The delegates met all through the summer and worked behind locked doors and closed windows to keep their meetings secret.  Throughout the meetings&#44; delegates threw temper tantrums&#44; and insulted one another.  Some even stomped out of the meetings and never returned.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:18:53', 'no', 'no', 0),
(519, 'The Great Compromise', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:19:54', 'no', 'no', 0),
(520, 'All the delegates wanted to create a representative form of government.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:20:25', 'no', 'no', 0),
(521, 'People would elect representatives&#44; and these representatives would make decisions for them.  ', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:21:13', 'no', 'no', 0),
(522, 'All the delegates wanted to have a Congress to make laws.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:22:41', 'no', 'no', 0),
(523, 'Each state would elect representatives to Congress.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:23:42', 'no', 'no', 0),
(524, 'But the delegates could not agree on how many representatives each state should have.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:24:13', 'no', 'no', 0),
(525, 'States with a lot of people thought that they should have more members than states with fewer people.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:25:01', 'no', 'no', 0),
(526, 'But states with fewer people didn&#39;t want the other states to have more power in Congress than they had&#44; so they thought all states should have the same number of members.  ', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:26:29', 'no', 'no', 0),
(527, 'A compromise&#44; called the Great Compromise&#44; settled the disagreement.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:32:30', 'no', 'no', 0),
(528, 'Congress would have two parts&#45;&#45;a Senate and a House of Representatives.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:33:01', 'no', 'no', 0),
(529, 'In one part&#44; the Senate&#44; each state would have the same number of members.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:33:49', 'no', 'no', 0),
(530, 'In the other part&#44; the House of Representatives&#44; states would have different numbers of members depending on how many people lived in each state.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:35:17', 'no', 'no', 0),
(531, 'States with more people would have more representatives.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:36:18', 'no', 'no', 0),
(532, 'James Madison', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:36:49', 'no', 'no', 0),
(533, 'This portrait was painted in 1816 when Madison was President. ', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:37:37', 'no', 'no', 0),
(534, 'More than anyone else&#44; it was James Madison whose words and ideas slowly convinced delegates that a new constitution and a strong central government were needed.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:39:05', 'no', 'no', 0),
(535, 'Madison made more than 150 speeches during the Constitutional Convention and wrote much of the Constitution.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:40:06', 'no', 'no', 0),
(536, 'He is known as the &#34;Father of the Constitution.&#34; ', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:40:37', 'no', 'no', 0),
(537, 'In 1788&#44; he wrote over a third of the Federalist Papers&#44; which encouraged states to ratify the Constitution.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:41:25', 'no', 'no', 0),
(538, 'Madison was responsible for the first ten amendments to the Constitution and is also known as the &#34;Father of the Bill of Rights.”', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:42:53', 'no', 'no', 0),
(539, 'In 1789&#44; Madison  was elected to the First United States Congress&#44; representing Virginia in the House of representatives.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:43:54', 'no', 'no', 0),
(540, 'He drafted many basic laws and  worked closely with President George Washington to organize the new federal government.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:44:25', 'no', 'no', 0),
(541, 'When Thomas Jefferson became  president  in 1801&#44;  he asked Madison to serve as Secretary of State.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:45:13', 'no', 'no', 0),
(542, 'As  Secretary of State &#40;1801–1809&#41;&#44; he  supervised the Louisiana Purchase which doubled the size of the new nation.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:46:41', 'no', 'no', 0),
(543, 'In 1809&#44; Madison became the fourth president of the United States and served two terms &#40;1809&#45;1817&#41;.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 10:47:42', 'no', 'no', 0),
(544, 'Overview of the Constitution', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-08 10:03:41', 'no', 'no', 0),
(545, 'The Constitution is made up of 3 parts&#44; the preamble&#44; the articles&#44; and the amendments.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-08 10:04:42', 'no', 'no', 0),
(546, 'When the delegates signed the Constitution on September 17&#44; 1787&#44; it contained the preamble and 7 articles.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:02:37', 'no', 'no', 0),
(547, 'In 1791&#44; the first 10 amendments&#44; the Bill of Rights&#44; were added. Since 1791&#44; 17 other amendments have been added to the Constitution. ', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:03:08', 'no', 'no', 0),
(548, 'The Constitution sets up a federal system of government which means power is shared between the national government and state governments.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:08:56', 'no', 'no', 0),
(549, 'Articles I&#44; II&#44; and III separate the power of the national government into 3 branches: legislative&#44; executive&#44; and judicial.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:10:24', 'no', 'no', 0),
(550, 'Other articles tell how to change and approve the Constitution and how states will work with each other and the national government. ', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:15:25', 'no', 'no', 0),
(551, 'The Constitution does not go into lots of detail.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:21:56', 'no', 'no', 0),
(552, 'It tells the legislative branch &#40;Congress&#41; to make the laws.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:25:57', 'no', 'no', 0),
(553, 'It tells the executive branch &#40;the president&#41; to carry out the laws made by Congress.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:29:07', 'no', 'no', 0),
(554, 'And it tells the the judicial branch &#40;the Supreme Court and other federal courts&#41; to settle any arguments or disagreements that arise from the Constitution. ', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-08 19:36:38', 'no', 'no', 0),
(555, 'Benjamin Banneker &#45;&#45; author, scientist, mathematician, farmer, astronomer, publisher and urban planner &#45;&#45; was descended from enslaved Africans, an indentured English servant, and free men and women of color.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:00:00', 'no', 'no', 0),
(556, 'His grandmother, Molly Welsh, was an English dairy maid who was falsely convicted of theft and indentured to a Maryland tobacco farmer.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:01:51', 'no', 'no', 0),
(557, 'After working out her indenture, Welsh rented and farmed some land, eventually purchasing two African slaves whom she freed several years later.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:04:29', 'no', 'no', 0),
(558, 'In violation of Maryland law, Welsh wed one of her former slaves, Bannke or Bannaka, said to be the son of a chief.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:04:39', 'no', 'no', 0),
(559, 'Their daughter Mary also married an African &#45;&#45; a man from Guinea who had been enslaved, baptized as Robert, and freed &#45;&#45; who took Banneker as his surname upon their marriage.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:05:10', 'no', 'no', 0),
(560, 'In 1731, they named their first child Benjamin.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:07:01', 'no', 'no', 0),
(561, 'Young Benjamin grew up in Baltimore County, one of two hundred free blacks among a population of four thousand slaves and thirteen thousand whites.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:09:39', 'no', 'no', 0),
(562, 'He was taught to read by his grandmother Molly, and briefly attended a one&#45;room interracial school taught by a Quaker. He showed an early interest in mathematics and mechanics, preferring books to play.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:12:49', 'no', 'no', 0),
(563, 'At the age of 22, having seen only two timepieces in his lifetime &#45;&#45; a sundial and a pocket watching &#45;&#45; Banneker constructed a striking clock almost entirely out of wood, based on his own drawings and calculations.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:15:59', 'no', 'no', 0),
(564, 'The clock continued to run until it was destroyed in a fire forty years later.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:17:50', 'no', 'no', 0),
(565, 'Banneker became friendly with the Ellicott brothers, who built a complex of gristmills in the 1770s.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:20:28', 'no', 'no', 0),
(566, 'Like Banneker, George Ellicott was a mathematician and amateur astronomer.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:23:38', 'no', 'no', 0),
(567, 'In 1788, with tools and books borrowed from Ellicott, Banneker nearly accurately predicted the timing of an eclipse of the sun, discovering later that his minor error was due to a discrepancy in his expert sources rather than a miscalculation on his part.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:26:48', 'no', 'no', 0),
(568, 'In 1791, Banneker accompanied Major Andrew Ellicott to the banks of the Potomac to assist him in surveying the new federal city that would become the nation&#39;s capital.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:28:39', 'no', 'no', 0),
(569, 'A notice first printed in the Georgetown Weekly Ledger and later copied in other newspapers stated that Ellicott was &#34;attended by Benjamin Banneker, an Ethiopian, whose abilities, as a surveyor, and an astronomer, clearly prove that Mr. Jefferson&#39;s concluding that race of men were void of mental endowments, was without foundation.&#34;', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:31:17', 'no', 'no', 0),
(570, 'In 1792, Banneker published an almanac, based on his own painstakingly calculated ephemeris (table of the position of celestial bodies), that also included commentaries, literature, and fillers that had a political and humanitarian purpose.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:34:27', 'no', 'no', 0),
(571, 'The previous summer, he had sent a copy of the ephemeris to Thomas Jefferson, along with a letter in which he challenged Jefferson&#39;s ideas about the inferiority of blacks.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:34:58', 'no', 'no', 0),
(572, 'Between 1792 and 1797, Banneker published six almanacs in twenty&#45;eight editions. He continued to live alone, selling off and renting his land, then giving the rest to the Ellicotts in exchange for a small pension.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:36:49', 'no', 'no', 0),
(573, 'He died in 1806. On the day of his burial, his house and its contents (including his clock) caught fire and burned to the ground. ', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-09 12:39:27', 'no', 'no', 0),
(574, 'Isaac Newton', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:00:00', 'no', 'no', 0),
(575, 'Lived 1643 to 1727.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:00:31', 'no', 'no', 0),
(576, 'Isaac Newton is perhaps the greatest physicist who has ever lived.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:02:22', 'no', 'no', 0),
(577, 'He and Albert Einstein are almost equally matched contenders for this title.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:05:00', 'no', 'no', 0),
(578, 'Each of these great scientists produced dramatic and startling transformations in the physical laws we believe our universe obeys, changing the way we understand and relate to the world around us.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:07:38', 'no', 'no', 0),
(579, 'Early Life and Education', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:08:09', 'no', 'no', 0),
(580, 'Isaac Newton was born on January 4, 1643 in the tiny village of Woolsthorpe&#45;by&#45;Colsterworth, Lincolnshire, England.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:10:00', 'no', 'no', 0),
(581, 'His father, whose name was also Isaac Newton, was a farmer who died before Isaac Junior was born. Although comfortable financially, his father could not read or write.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:12:38', 'no', 'no', 0),
(582, 'His mother, Hannah Ayscough, married a churchman when Newton was three years old.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:15:16', 'no', 'no', 0),
(583, 'Newton disliked his mother&#39;s new husband and did not join their household, living instead with his mother&#39;s mother, Margery Ayscough.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:17:54', 'no', 'no', 0),
(584, 'His resentment of his mother and stepfather&#39;s new life did not subside with time; as a teenager he threatened to burn their house down!', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:19:45', 'no', 'no', 0),
(585, 'Beginning at age 12, Newton attended The King&#39;s School, Grantham, where he was taught the classics, but no science or mathematics.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:22:23', 'no', 'no', 0),
(586, 'When he was 17, his mother stopped his schooling so that he could become a farmer. Fortunately for the future of science Newton found he had neither aptitude nor liking for farming; his mother allowed him to return to school, where he finished as top student.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:25:01', 'no', 'no', 0),
(587, 'Servant and Undergraduate', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:25:32', 'no', 'no', 0),
(588, 'In June 1661, aged 18, Newton began studying for a law degree at Cambridge University&#39;s Trinity College, earning money working as a personal servant to wealthier students.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:27:23', 'no', 'no', 0),
(589, 'By the time he was a third&#45;year student he was spending a lot of his time studying mathematics and natural philosophy (today we call it physics).', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:30:01', 'no', 'no', 0),
(590, 'He was also very interested in alchemy, which we now categorize as a pseudoscience.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:30:11', 'no', 'no', 0),
(591, 'His natural philosophy lecturers based their courses on Aristotle&#39;s incorrect ideas from Ancient Greece.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:30:42', 'no', 'no', 0),
(592, 'This was despite the fact that 25 years earlier, in 1638, Galileo Galilei had published his physics masterpiece Two New Sciences establishing a new scientific basis for the physics of motion.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:32:33', 'no', 'no', 0),
(593, 'Newton began to disregard the material taught at his college, preferring to study the recent (and more scientifically correct) works of Galileo, Boyle, Descartes, and Kepler. He wrote:', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:35:11', 'no', 'no', 0),
(594, 'Isaac Newton&#34;Plato is my friend, Aristotle is my friend, but my greatest friend is truth.&#34;', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:37:49', 'no', 'no', 0),
(595, 'Isaac Newton Mathematician and Physicist', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:38:20', 'no', 'no', 0),
(596, 'Reading the works of these great scientists, Newton grew more ambitious about making discoveries himself. While still working part&#45;time as a servant, he wrote a note to himself.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:40:11', 'no', 'no', 0),
(597, 'In it he posed questions which had not yet been answered by science. These included questions about gravity, the nature of light, the nature of color and vision, and atoms.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:42:49', 'no', 'no', 0),
(598, 'After three years at Cambridge he won a four&#45;year scholarship, allowing him to devote his time fully to academic studies.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-05 12:45:27', 'no', 'no', 0),
(599, 'Rediscovering Ramanujan', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:00:00', 'no', 'no', 0),
(600, 'My Search for Ramanujan: How I Learned to Count; Ken Ono & Amir D. Aczel, Springer.  ', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:01:51', 'no', 'no', 0),
(601, 'Mathematician Ken Ono on how a chance letter from Ramanujan&#39;s wife changed the way he looked not only at the world of numbers but at life itself.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:04:29', 'no', 'no', 0),
(602, 'In the pursuit of sharply&#45;defined goals, we can at times forget that the journey itself holds riches that, by far, outweigh the goals.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:04:39', 'no', 'no', 0),
(603, 'Life&#39;s journeys hold all kinds of signs and messages that reveal new destinations that are far more intimately connected with the self than with preset goals.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:05:10', 'no', 'no', 0),
(604, 'My Search for Ramanujan is the story of one such journey.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:07:01', 'no', 'no', 0),
(605, 'The first author of the book, mathematician Ken Ono, is a professor at Emory University. Born to Sachiko and Takashi Ono, who was himself a leading mathematician, Ono&#39;s future in mathematics appeared set.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:09:39', 'no', 'no', 0),
(606, 'However (and that&#39;s what this book is about), his life was far from being smooth or dictated by logic.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:12:17', 'no', 'no', 0),
(607, 'Ono had to undertake his own version of a hero&#39;s journey before coming in contact with a mathematics he could call his own; before, in fact, being able to embrace with love his &#34;tiger parents&#34;.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:12:48', 'no', 'no', 0),
(608, 'Ono was, even as a child, groomed to become a first&#45;class mathematician, and the demands played havoc with his self&#45;esteem. Being a prodigiously talented teenager did not help either.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:14:39', 'no', 'no', 0),
(609, 'Violin lessons and mathematics were the two activities he was encouraged to focus upon. And focus he did, at great expense to his self&#45;worth and motivation.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:17:17', 'no', 'no', 0),
(610, 'As it happened, when the pressure rose to an intolerable degree, he decided to quit music lessons and school.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:17:27', 'no', 'no', 0),
(611, 'The day he decided to quit and break the news to his father, a letter arrived from Janaki Ammal, widow of renowned mathematician Srinivasa Ramanujan.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:17:58', 'no', 'no', 0),
(612, 'In the letter, Janaki thanked Ono&#39;s father for making a contribution towards building a small statue of Ramanujan.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:19:49', 'no', 'no', 0),
(613, 'Ono harboured no real hope of his father permitting him to leave school. Strangely, perhaps triggered by Janaki&#39;s letter, his father — with his thoughts now dwelling on how Ramanujan&#39;s life was tragically cut short by neglect, malnutrition and tuberculosis —half&#45;heartedly accepted Ono&#39;s idea of taking a break and going bike tour.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:22:27', 'no', 'no', 0),
(614, 'Ono undertook his journey around the world, where he ultimately found mentors, mathematics and freedom from the voices of disapproval he had internalised. His journey took him full circle, and he finally returned home to make peace with his parents.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:25:05', 'no', 'no', 0),
(615, 'Despite being brought up to deny anything irrational, he even went on a ‘pilgrimage&#39; to Kumbakonam, Ramanujan&#39;s birthplace, where more signs and treasures awaited him.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:27:43', 'no', 'no', 0),
(616, 'The journey is, at one level, literally that, as Ono moved from place to place, institute to institute, learning, teaching, failing, recovering and, most importantly, discovering the mathematics of Ramanujan.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:29:34', 'no', 'no', 0),
(617, 'There are many other threads to Ono&#39;s complex story — an Asian&#45;American teenager growing up at the interface of incompatible cultures and breaking free; an arc of recovery of an individual suffering from low self&#45;esteem and lack of motivation; a young, bright mathematician moving from bookish knowledge to an appreciation of what is divine about math.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:32:12', 'no', 'no', 0),
(618, 'The long sections devoted to describing his life story apart, Ramanujan makes his presence felt in other ways too. Beckoning from his world of numbers, Ramanujan slowly reveals the secrets of his mathematics to Ono. Subtly, the reader is drawn to understand the difference between problem&#45;solving and theory&#45;building in mathematics, and how Ramanujan fits into neither category, but is an anticipator of mathematics.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:34:50', 'no', 'no', 0),
(619, 'In his short lifetime and brief stint at Trinity College, Ramanujan spewed out ideas and theorems on number theory at a furious rate.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:35:21', 'no', 'no', 0),
(620, 'Ramanujan was a supernova among mathematicians, throwing out multiple ideas, which no one recognised then and few do now.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:37:12', 'no', 'no', 0),
(621, 'Guided by this presence, and nurtured by mathematicians such as Basil Gordon and Paul Sally, to whom this book is dedicated, Ono chooses to work on the underlying theories in the apparently disconnected statements made by Ramanujan, and not just work on his ideas.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:39:50', 'no', 'no', 0),
(622, 'Ramanujan used to jot down his ideas methodically in notebooks, in green ink.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:42:28', 'no', 'no', 0),
(623, 'One of these, called the ‘lost notebook&#39;, was discovered in the Trinity College library by mathematician George Andrews in 1976, and later published as a book.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:42:59', 'no', 'no', 0),
(624, 'Ono made a discovery about elliptic curves recently that was prompted by Ramanujan&#39;s comments in his notebooks.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:44:50', 'no', 'no', 0),
(625, 'Ono and his co&#45;author Amir D. Aczel have woven real&#45;life incidents into a story that is engaging while prodding the reader to explore the world. The book will make a great turning point not only for young and aspiring mathematicians but also for others who have a voice in their heads telling them they are on the wrong road.', 'denny_crane', 'none', '2016-07-07 12:47:28', 'no', 'no', 0),
